title: A Multi-centre, Double-blind, Parallel-group, Randomized Controlled Study to Investigate the Efficacy, Safety and Tolerability of Orally Administered BI 409306 During a 12-week Treatment Period Compared to Placebo in Patients With Alzheimer Disease
description_brief: The study is designed to compare the effects of 4 different doses of orally administered BI 409306 to placebo in patients with Alzheimers Disease

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: For this trial, patients were randomised at 36 sites in 11 countries. Following an initial Screening Visit and a single blinded 2-week placebo run-in period, patients who qualified according to the in- and exclusion criteria were randomised to one of the five treatment groups
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: A multi-centre, double-blind, parallel-group, randomized controlled study to investigate the efficacy, safety and tolerability of orally administered BI 409306 during a 12-week treatment period compared to placebo in patients with Alzheimer's Disease

measures.title: Neuropsychological Test Battery (NTB) Total
measures.description: Baseline cognitive assessment data- NTB total z-score. The NTB consists of 9 validated components. Raw scores on each of the 9 NTB tests were converted to z-scores using the baseline means and standard deviations (SDs) for each test. The resultant z-scores were averaged to obtain a total z-score, incorporating all 9 NTB tests. The NTB Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations away from the mean. A Z-score of 0 is equal to the mean at baseline. Higher values indicate a better Outcome

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Neuropsychological Test Battery in Total Z-score After 12-week Treatment.
outcomeMeasures.description: Neuropsychological Test Battery (NTB) response, defined as change from baseline in total z-score after 12 weeks of treatment. The NTB Z-score indicates the number of standard deviations away from the mean. A Z-score of 0 is equal to the mean at baseline. Negative numbers indicate values lower than baseline and positive numbers indicate values higher than baseline. Change from baseline will be calculated as the post-baseline composite z-score minus the pre-treatment z-score, such that a positive change indicates an improvement from baseline

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in ADCS-MCI-ADL (Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study/Activities of Daily Living for Patients With Mild Cognitive Impairment) Total Score After 12-week Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description:
Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study/Activities of Daily Living (ADCS-ADL) is a rating scale used to assess basic and instrumental activities of daily living. In the full version of the scale, 23 items are rated by the investigator using information supplied by the caregiver.

Each item has a score range varying from 0-3 to 0-5. The sum score can range from 0 to 78. Higher scores indicate better function.

Least Squares Mean is actually an adjusted mean change from baseline.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Clinical Dementia Rating Scale Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) Total Score After 12-week Treatment
outcomeMeasures.description:
The CDR-SB is obtained through semi-structured interviews of patients and informants, and cognitive functioning was rated in 6 domains of functioning: memory, orientation, judgment and problem solving, community affairs, home and hobbies and personal care.

Each domain was rated on a 5-point scale of functioning as follows: 0-no impairment; 0.5-questionable impairment; 1-mild impairment; 2-moderate impairment and 3-severe impairment. Only personal care was scored on a 4-point scale without a 0.5 rating available. The higher the score, the greater the severity of dementia. Least Squares Mean is actually an adjusted mean change from baseline.

certainAgreement.otherDetails: Boehringer Ingelheim (BI) acknowledges that investigators have the right to publish the study results. Investigators shall provide BI with a copy of any publication or presentation for review prior to any submission. Such review will be done with regard to proprietary information, information related to patentable inventions, medical, scientific, and statistical accuracy within 60 days. BI may request a delay of the publication in order to protect BI's intellectual property rights.

explanation_target: Reason: BI 409306 is a potent, selective phosphodiesterase‑9A (PDE9A) inhibitor — a small‑molecule intended to increase cGMP, promote synaptic plasticity and improve memory/cognition rather than to remove amyloid or tau pathology. citeturn0search3turn0search8

Act: The trial description (oral BI 409306, four dose levels vs placebo, 12‑week treatment, cognitive endpoints such as the Neuropsychological Test Battery/ADAS‑Cog/CDR‑SB) matches published Phase II studies testing BI 409306 for symptomatic cognitive improvement in prodromal/mild Alzheimer’s disease. These studies evaluated cognitive outcomes and did not target amyloid or tau directly. citeturn0search2turn0search3

Reflect: Given the intervention is a small‑molecule PDE9A inhibitor developed to enhance cognition (mechanism: raise cGMP and facilitate synaptic plasticity) and the trial endpoints are cognitive/symptomatic, the appropriate category is 'Cognitive enhancer' rather than a disease‑targeted biologic or disease‑targeted small molecule. Published pooled Phase II results showed no significant cognitive benefit but confirm the drug’s intended use as a symptomatic cognitive enhancer. citeturn0search3turn0search0

Web search sources used (key results): (1) Pooled Phase II report (Alzheimer’s Research & Therapy / PMC) describing 12‑week, multi‑dose oral BI 409306 trials in prodromal/mild AD and negative efficacy results. citeturn0search3 (2) PubMed abstract summarizing the Phase II studies and endpoints. citeturn0search0 (3) Phase I proof‑of‑mechanism study showing BI 409306 increases CSF cGMP (target engagement). citeturn0search1 (4) Preclinical study demonstrating increased brain cGMP, enhanced LTP and improved memory in rodents (supports cognitive‑enhancer mechanism). citeturn0search8 (5) Phase I safety/PK overview describing BI 409306 as a selective PDE9A inhibitor. citeturn0search5
explanation_agent: Reason: BI 409306 is a selective phosphodiesterase‑9A (PDE9A) inhibitor designed to raise cGMP and enhance synaptic signaling/plasticity to improve memory/cognition (a symptomatic cognitive‑enhancer mechanism), not to target amyloid, tau, ApoE, vasculature, etc. citeturn0search0turn0search3

Act: Extracted details — oral small‑molecule BI 409306 (PDE9A inhibitor), 12‑week randomized studies with cognitive endpoints (NTB, ADAS‑Cog, CDR‑SB) testing symptomatic cognitive benefit rather than amyloid/tau removal. These Phase II studies pooled 457 patients and showed no cognitive benefit but confirm the intended synaptic‑plasticity/cognitive‑enhancer mechanism. citeturn0search3turn0search1

Reflect: Mapping to CADRO, the intervention’s primary biological focus is enhancing synaptic function/plasticity (increase cGMP, facilitate LTP and cognition), which corresponds to M) Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection. The classification excludes disease‑modifying categories (A/B/I etc.) because the mechanism is symptomatic/signal‑modifying. Program discontinuation reports and full publications corroborate this interpretation. citeturn0search5turn0search3

Web search results (key sources used): (1) Phase I proof‑of‑mechanism showing BI 409306 increases CSF cGMP (target engagement). citeturn0search0 (2) PubMed entry summarizing the two Phase II RCTs in prodromal/mild AD (design/mechanism). citeturn0search1 (3) Full pooled Phase II report (Alzheimer’s Research & Therapy) with endpoints, 12‑week treatment, and negative efficacy results. citeturn0search3 (4) Industry coverage noting BI 409306 was intended to restore signaling/glutamatergic circuit function (symptomatic approach) and program wind‑down after negative results. citeturn0search5
